LABEL: Cluster ID
DEFINITION: Clusters were the unit of randomization, and each consisted of 1 or more administrative villages. Two or more neighboring may have been combined to create 1 cluster as long as the cluster of villages had at least 8 eligible pregnant women and shared a border.

LABEL: Cluster ID
DEFINITION: Clusters--defined as one health sub-district--were randomly assigned to one of four study arms. 104 clusters cover 48 districts in Eastern and Western Uganda, and were the unit of randomization for intervention assignment.

LABEL: Cluster ID
DEFINITION: The unit of randomization. A cluster consisted of a group of 8 proximate compounds (multiple households sharing a common courtyard) within a village that were visited by a single local promoter. Clusters were separated from each other by at least a 15 min walk (1 km).

LABEL: Cluster as-treated
DEFINITION: The type of long-lasting insecticide-treated bednet (LLIN) received by the cluster during the 2016-2017 Universal Coverage Campaign (UCC), for the as-treated analysis. LLINs were distributed to clusters after the baseline survey was performed at the 0 month 'Study timepoint'. Certain clusters received a different LLIN type than that which was originally assigned to that cluster ('Cluster study arm'). For the as-treated analysis, clusters were grouped by type of LLINs received according to household data from the 6-month study timepoint ('UCC LLIN type'). For clusters with mixed LLIN distribution, the number of LLINs from the dominant type received was divided by the total number of LLINs received in that cluster; non-study nets were excluded. To be included in the as-treated analyses, the proportion of the dominant LLIN had to be more than 75%. 'Cluster as-treated' analyses were presented as the main study findings.

LABEL: Cluster as-treated, dichotomized
DEFINITION: The type of long-lasting insecticide-treated bednet (LLIN) received by the cluster during the 2016-2017 Universal Coverage Campaign (UCC), for the as-treated analysis. LLINs were distributed to clusters after the baseline survey was performed at the 0 month 'Study timepoint'. Clusters received either conventional LLINs or LLINs containing piperonyl butoxide (PBO). Conventional LLINs include PermaNet 2.0 and Olyset Net. PBO LLINs include PermaNet 3.0 and Olyset Plus. Certain clusters received a different LLIN type than that which was originally assigned to that cluster ('Cluster study arm'). For the as-treated analysis, clusters were grouped by type of LLINs received according to household data from the 6-month study timepoint ('UCC LLIN type'). For clusters with mixed LLIN distribution, the number of LLINs from the dominant type received was divided by the total number of LLINs received in that cluster; non-study nets were excluded. To be included in the as-treated analyses, the proportion of the dominant LLIN had to be more than 75%. 'Cluster as-treated' analyses were presented as the main study findings.

LABEL: Cluster study arm
DEFINITION: Both arms were provided supplies to screen and treat syphilis. The intervention arm used behavioral strategies including selection of opinion leaders, academic detailing visits with antenatal care providers, reminders, audits and feedback, supportive supervision, and the preparation of kits with the supplies for syphilis screening and treatment with the goal of improving rates of syphilis screening and treating.

LABEL: Cluster study arm
DEFINITION: The actual randomized, blinded intervention assigned to the cluster. The passive control arm enabled measurement of the effect of regular promoter visits in the active control arm.

LABEL: Cluster study arm
DEFINITION: The actual randomized, blinded intervention assigned to the compound. Compounds consisted of multiple households (typically 3 to 10 in Bangladesh), usually comprised of blood relatives, who share a common courtyard. Groups of 8 proximate compounds were assigned to a cluster, and each randomization block was made up of 8 adjacent clusters that were pair-matched by geography. Each cluster within the randomization block was randomly allocated to one of 7 study arms, including 2 clusters randomly allocated to the control arm. A description of each study arm can be found on the study details page.

LABEL: Cluster study arm, dichotomized

Clusters were randomized to receive either conventional long-lasting insecticide-treated bednets (LLINs) or LLINs containing piperonyl butoxide (PBO). Lighting source
DEFINITION: A light source is an optical subsystem that provides light for use in a distant area using a delivery system (e.g., fiber optics). Light sources may include one of a variety of lamps (e.g., xenon, halogen, mercury). Most light sources are operated from line power, but some may be powered from batteries. They are mostly used in endoscopic, microscopic, and other examination and/or in surgical procedures. The light source is part of the optical subsystem. In a flow cytometer the light source directs high intensity light at particles at the interrogation point. The light source in a flow cytometer is usually a laser.

LABEL: A-not-B score
DEFINITION: To assess object permanence and working memory, the child watched as a treat was hidden under 1 of 2 bowls (A or B); after a brief delay, the child was asked to find the treat under one of the bowls, remembering where it was. The exercise was repeated 10 times, switching which bowl the treat was hidden under according to protocol for all 10 episodes to check that the child had no perseveration error. The score reflects the number of times they correctly identified where a treat was hidden out of 10 episodes.

LABEL: Polio serotype 1 seroconversion failure
DEFINITION: Seroconversion failure was derived based on the child's serum neutralizing antibodies (SNA) at 40 weeks (SNAwk40) and the maternal-antibody adjusted SNA at 18 weeks (SNAwk18). The participant was considered to have failed to seroconvert if a) SNAwk18 <= 2.833 and SNAwk40 <= 3 or b)  2.833 < SNAwk18 <= 8.5 and (SNAwk40 - SNAwk18) < 2 or c) 8.5 < SNAwk18 <10.5 and SNAwk40 < 10.5. Participants with SNAwk18  >= 10.5 were excluded.

LABEL: Polio serotype 2 seroconversion failure
DEFINITION: Seroconversion failure was derived based on the child's serum neutralizing antibodies (SNA) at 40 weeks (SNAwk40) and the maternal-antibody adjusted SNA at 18 weeks (SNAwk18). The participant was considered to have failed to seroconvert if a) SNAwk18 <= 2.833 and SNAwk40 <= 3 or b)  2.833 < SNAwk18 <= 8.5 and (SNAwk40 - SNAwk18) < 2 or c) 8.5 < SNAwk18 <10.5 and SNAwk40 < 10.5. Participants with SNAwk18  >= 10.5 were excluded.

LABEL: Polio serotype 3 seroconversion failure
DEFINITION: Seroconversion failure was derived based on the child's serum neutralizing antibodies (SNA) at 40 weeks (SNAwk40) and the maternal-antibody adjusted SNA at 18 weeks (SNAwk18). The participant was considered to have failed to seroconvert if a) SNAwk18 <= 2.833 and SNAwk40 <= 3 or b)  2.833 < SNAwk18 <= 8.5 and (SNAwk40 - SNAwk18) < 2 or c) 8.5 < SNAwk18 <10.5 and SNAwk40 < 10.5. Participants with SNAwk18  >= 10.5 were excluded.

LABEL: Polio vaccination dose per protocol
DEFINITION: Whether the participant received all intervention doses even if outside the visit window. The justification for relaxing the vaccination window requirement is partially based on the WHO recommendations which emphasize getting the required doses rather than exact ages for receiving the doses and the pragmatic concern of how far outside the window do we set the threshold.

LABEL: Polio vaccination per protocol
DEFINITION: Whether strictly per protocol as described here. DEFINITION: Total time (originally reported in days) falling within any diarrheal episode since beginning of follow-up. Diarrhea episodes were separated by two diarrhea-free days. Surveillance was conducted twice weekly for up to 3 years of age to assess illness on all days since the last surveillance visit.

LABEL: Total time in all diarrheal episodes, excluding 1st days
DEFINITION: Total time (originally reported in days) falling within any diarrheal episode during follow-up, excluding the first day of each diarrheal episode. Diarrhea episodes were separated by two diarrhea-free days. Days when data were missing were classified as diarrhea-free (if there were two missing days before a day with diarrhea, the episode started on day with diarrhea). LABEL: L:M analysis date
DEFINITION: Date urine sample underwent Lactulose:Mannitol (L:M) analysis by the laboratory. The Lactulose:Mannitol dual sugar test for gut permeability was used for analysis of environmental enteropathy and was assessed in urine samples collected at 3, 6, 9, and 15 months of age.

LABEL: L:M analysis lab
DEFINITION: Laboratory that conducted the Lactulose:Mannitol (L:M) HPLC assay. The Lactulose:Mannitol dual sugar test for gut permeability was used for analysis of environmental enteropathy and was assessed in urine samples collected at 3, 6, 9, and 15 months of age.

LABEL: L:M excretion ratio
DEFINITION: Assessed at 12, 24, 40, and 104 weeks.

LABEL: L:M excretion ratio
DEFINITION: Test performed at week 12 (month 3) and week 52 (month 12) for a subset of participants

LABEL: L:M excretion test 1 day before stool collection
DEFINITION: Flag if the lactulose:mannitol test was given the day of or the day before the date of stool collection. First monthly asymptomatic stool samples should not have been collected within 48hrs after administration of the Lactulose:Mannitol (L:M) solution as it interferes with the gut inflammation biomarker assays. Whenever a participant produced at least 3 loose stools in a single day, diarrheal stool samples were collected before the end of the episode. First monthly asymptomatic stool samples were collected every month from 0-24 months of age, with a possible extension to 36 months of age. First monthly asymptomatic stool samples collected at 1-12, 15, 18, 21, and 24 months of age were included in analyses of gut function.

LABEL: L:M solution volume

LABEL: Lost to follow-up within 14 days of stool collection
DEFINITION: Whether the participant was lost to follow-up, but the length of time with surveillance data before or after stool collection was less than 14 days. This variable determines whether there was sufficient follow-up to create 'Stool type, 14 day window,' an alternative stool type definition. First monthly asymptomatic stool samples were collected every month from 0-24 months of age, with a possible extension to 36 months of age. Surveillance was conducted twice weekly for up to 3 years of age to assess illness on all days since the last surveillance visit. Whenever a participant produced at least 3 loose stools in a single day, diarrheal stool samples were collected before the end of the episode.

Surveillance was conducted twice weekly for up to 3 years of age to assess illness on all days since the last surveillance visit. Whenever a participant produced at least 3 loose stools in a single day, diarrheal stool samples were collected before the end of the episode.

LABEL: Parasite asexual lifecycle stage, by microscopy
DEFINITION: A parasite lifecycle stage that occurs as a result of asexual replication in the red blood cells of the host organism. For Plasmodium species these stages can include merozoites, trophozoites, and schizonts.

LABEL: Parasite count
DEFINITION: Sum of all parasite species ('Ascaris lumbricoides, by microscopy;' 'Balantidium coli, by microscopy;' 'Chilomastix mesnili, by microscopy;' 'Cryptosporidium, by ELISA;' 'Cyclospora, by microscopy;' 'Entamoeba histolytica, by ELISA;' 'Endolimax nana, by microscopy;' 'Enterobius vermicularis, by microscopy;' 'Giardia, by ELISA;' 'Hymenolepis diminuta, by microscopy;' 'Hymenolepis nana, by microscopy;' 'Hookworm, by microscopy;' 'Iodamoeba butschlii, by microscopy;' 'Isospora, by microscopy;' 'Strongyloides stercoralis, by microscopy;' 'Schistosoma, by microscopy;' 'Trichuris trichiura, by microscopy;' and 'Taenia, by microscopy') identified in this specific stool sample. Whenever a participant produced at least 3 loose stools in a single day, diarrheal stool samples were collected before the end of the episode. Work up for detection of enteric pathogens was performed on the first stool sample collected during each diarrheal episode until 24 months of age (with a possible extension to 36 months of age) and on first monthly asymptomatic stool samples collected at 1-12, 15, 18, 21, and 24 months of age (with the option to test additional monthly stool samples to 36 months of age).

LABEL: Parasites, by microscopy
DEFINITION: A eukaryota in feces datum that specifies whether a parasite organism was detected by microscopy assay.

LABEL: Pathogen (excluding NRV) count
DEFINITION: Sum of unique pathogen species (except for Norovirus) identified in this specific stool sample. Calculated for 1st monthly stool samples and 1st diarrheal stool samples, and requires complete testing. Whenever a participant produced at least 3 loose stools in a single day, diarrheal stool samples were collected before the end of the episode. Work up for detection of enteric pathogens was performed on diarrheal stool samples collected until 24 months of age (with a possible extension to 36 months of age) and on first monthly asymptomatic stool samples collected at 1-12, 15, 18, 21, and 24 months of age (with the option to test additional monthly stool samples to 36 months of age).

LABEL: Pathogen (excluding NRV) count, analysis monthly and per protocol diarrheal stools
DEFINITION: Sum of unique pathogen species (excluding Norovirus) identified in this specific stool sample. Calculated for "Analysis stool, monthly" samples and all "Per protocol diarrheal stool collection" samples protocol-compliant diarrhea stool samples (including "Analysis stool, diarrhea" samples and also diarrhea stool samples collected after 14 study-defined diarrhea days), and requires complete testing. Whenever a participant produced at least 3 loose stools in a single day, diarrheal stool samples were collected before the end of the episode. Work up for detection of enteric pathogens was performed on diarrheal stool samples collected until 24 months of age (with a possible extension to 36 months of age) and on first monthly asymptomatic stool samples collected at 1-12, 15, 18, 21, and 24 months of age (with the option to test additional monthly stool samples to 36 months of age).

DEFINITION: Sum of unique pathogen species identified in this specific stool sample. Calculated for 1st monthly stool samples and 1st diarrheal stool samples, and requires complete testing. Work up for detection of enteric pathogens was performed on diarrheal stool samples collected until 24 months of age (with a possible extension to 36 months of age) and on first monthly asymptomatic stool samples collected at 1-12, 15, 18, 21, and 24 months of age (with the option to test additional monthly stool samples to 36 months of age).

LABEL: Pathogen count, analysis monthly and per protocol diarrheal stools
DEFINITION: Sum of unique pathogen species identified in this specific stool sample. Calculated for "Analysis stool, monthly" samples and all "Per protocol diarrheal stool collection" samples protocol-compliant diarrhea stool samples (including "Analysis stool, diarrhea" samples and also diarrhea stool samples collected after 14 study-defined diarrhea days), and requires complete testing. Whenever a participant produced at least 3 loose stools in a single day, diarrheal stool samples were collected before the end of the episode. Work up for detection of enteric pathogens was performed on diarrheal stool samples collected until 24 months of age (with a possible extension to 36 months of age) and on first monthly asymptomatic stool samples collected at 1-12, 15, 18, 21, and 24 months of age (with the option to test additional monthly stool samples to 36 months of age).

LABEL: Pathogen count, analysis monthly stools
DEFINITION: Sum of unique pathogen species identified in this specific analysis monthly stool sample. Complete testing of stool samples is required to calculate this variable. Work up for detection of enteric pathogens was performed on first monthly asymptomatic stool samples collected at 1-12, 15, 18, 21, and 24 months of age (with the option to test additional monthly stool samples to 36 months of age).

LABEL: Pathogen count, by normalized PCR
DEFINITION: Number of pathogens detected on nasopharyngeal/oropharyngeal PCR, after applying the quantitative density threshold for the following pathogens: Pneumocystis jirovecii - 4 log10 copies/mL; Haemophilus influenzae - 5.9 log10 copies/mL; cytomegalovirus - 4.9 log10 copies/mL; Streptococcus pneumoniae - 6.9 log10 copies/mL.
PARENT_LABEL: Test result summary for nasopharyngeal/oropharyngeal swabs

LABEL: Pathogen count, per protocol diarrheal stools
DEFINITION: Sum of unique pathogen species identified in this specific per protocol diarrheal stool sample. Complete testing of stool samples is required to calculate this variable. Whenever a participant produced at least 3 loose stools in a single day, diarrheal stool samples were collected before the end of the episode. Work up for detection of enteric pathogens was performed on diarrheal stool samples collected until 24 months of age (with a possible extension to 36 months of age).

LABEL: Penicillin
DEFINITION: Assessed at enrollment for cases and controls

LABEL: Per protocol diarrheal stool collection
DEFINITION: Whether this diarrheal stool sample was collected per the MAL-ED study protocol. Per protocol diarrheal stools included samples collected before the end of each diarrheal episode (whenever a participant produced at least 3 loose stools in a single day) as well as additional stool samples collected for a specific diarrhea episode after 14 study-defined diarrhea days in the same episode. Whenever a participant produced at least 3 loose stools in a single day, diarrheal stool samples were collected before the end of the episode. Diarrheal stool samples were collected until 36 months of age.

LABEL: Per protocol stool collection
DEFINITION: Whether this was a per protocol stool collection, as defined by the MAL-ED Gut Function Technical Subcommittee. Per protocol first monthly asymptomatic stool samples were collected at 1-12, 15, 18, 21, and 24 months of age. Per protocol diarrhea stool samples were collected on a day that falls within a diarrheal episode or where the last diarrheal episode ended less than or equal to 7 days ago.

LABEL: Peripheral blood mononuclear cell sample
DEFINITION: PBMC

LABEL: Pertactin IgG titer, by MIA result
DEFINITION: A multiplexed immuno assay was used. Pertactin (PRN) is included in pertussis vaccines. Values below 1 EU/mL or below the standard curve were set to 1 EU/mL. Assessed at 53 weeks.

LABEL: Pertussis antibodies, by ELISA
DEFINITION: Positive pertussis titer (>38 IU/L at 7m or >26 IU/L at 15m of age), by ELISA. Antibody titers in response to vaccination and/or natural exposure were assessed in blood samples collected at 7 and 15 months of age.

LABEL: Pertussis titer, by ELISA result
DEFINITION: Pertussis titer (originally reported in IU/mL) in log2 scale. If pertussis titer is 0, log2(pertussis titer) is set to 0. Antibody titers in response to vaccination and/or natural exposure were assessed in blood samples collected at 7 and 15 months of age.

LABEL: Pertussis toxin IgG titer, by MIA result
DEFINITION: A multiplexed immuno assay was used. Values >62.5 EU/mL are indicative for infection in the past year. Values >125 EU/mL are indicitive for recent infection. Values below 1 EU/mL or below the standard curve were set to 1 EU/mL. Assessed at 53 weeks.

LABEL: Phocine herpesvirus (positive control), by TAC result
DEFINITION: Phocine herpes virus was spiked into every stool sample to control for extraction and amplification. 2 replicates were performed and both needed to succeed to have the stool sample included in analyses. Failure indicates that the sample was either inhibited, amplification failed, and/or extraction failed. Only assessed for diarrheal stools for participants from the 3000 series in site 1. Ct value of 40 indicates the organism was not detected

LABEL: Phocine herpesvirus (positive control), by TAC result
DEFINITION: Phocine herpes virus was spiked into every stool sample to control for extraction and amplification. Failure indicates that the sample was either inhibited, amplification failed, and/or extraction failed. For diarrheal stool samples, but not week 6 or week 10 stool samples, Ct values >= 35 are displayed as 35. Ct values of >= 35 are considered negative. For week 6 and week 10 samples, values of >= 35 are displayed as 0 and considered negative.

LABEL: Phocine herpesvirus (positive control), by TAC result 2
DEFINITION: Phocine herpes virus was spiked into every stool sample to control for extraction and amplification. 2 replicates were performed and both needed to succeed to have the stool sample included in analyses. Failure indicates that the sample was either inhibited, amplification failed, and/or extraction failed. Only assessed for diarrheal stools for participants from the 3000 series in site 1. Ct value of 40 indicates the organism was not detected

Work up for detection of enteric pathogens was performed on the first stool sample collected during each diarrheal episode until 24 months of age (with a possible extension to 36 months of age) and on first monthly asymptomatic stool samples collected at 1-12, 15, 18, 21, and 24 months of age (with the option to test additional monthly stool samples to 36 months of age).

LABEL: Quantity not sufficient
DEFINITION: Flag for monthly asymptomatic and diarrheal stool samples where the quantity collected was not sufficient (defined as less than 2 grams for monthly archive-only stools, and less than 4 grams for all other monthly and diarrheal stools). Recollection was requested for stool samples with insufficient quantities. Whenever a participant produced at least 3 loose stools in a single day, diarrheal stool samples were collected before the end of the episode. First monthly asymptomatic stool samples were collected every month from 0-24 months of age, with a possible extension to 36 months of age. First monthly asymptomatic samples collected at 13-14, 16-17, 19-20, 22-23 and 25-36 months of age were for archive only.

LABEL: Rotavirus (post-vax corrected), by ELISA
DEFINITION: Whether Rotavirus was detected by ELISA for this stool sample. Any positive Rotavirus test result within 28 days of Rotavirus vaccination was changed to be a negative result. Whenever a participant produced at least 3 loose stools in a single day, diarrheal stool samples were collected before the end of the episode. Work up for detection of enteric pathogens was performed on the first stool sample collected during each diarrheal episode until 24 months of age (with a possible extension to 36 months of age) and on first monthly asymptomatic stool samples collected at 1-12, 15, 18, 21, and 24 months of age (with the option to test additional monthly stool samples to 36 months of age).

LABEL: Rotavirus (post-vax corrected), by TAC result

Quantitative PCR for detection of enteric pathogens via TAC was performed on all available diarrheal and monthly asymptomatic stool samples collected from 0-24 months and at 60 months of age.

DEFINITION: Type of stool type collected, using information from surveillance. 'Diarrhea stools' were samples where diarrhea was reported within +/- 2 days of stool collection. 'Monthly stools' were collected more than 7 days away from an episode of study-defined diarrhea. Surveillance was conducted twice weekly for up to 3 years of age to assess illness on all days since the last surveillance visit. LABEL: Stool type, gut function
DEFINITION: Stool type definition from the MAL-ED Gut Function Technical Subcommittee. 'Other stools' were samples where diarrhea was reported within the preceding 7 days and/or the lactulose:mannitol test was performed on the day of or day before stool collection. 'Asymptomatic stools' were stool samples that did not meet this definition of 'Other stools.' Only 'Asymptomatic stools' were included in the gut function analysis set used in PMID: 28396264. Surveillance was conducted twice weekly for up to 3 years of age to assess illness on all days since the last surveillance visit. Whenever a participant produced at least 3 loose stools in a single day, diarrheal stool samples were collected before the end of the episode. First monthly asymptomatic stool samples were collected every month from 0-24 months of age, with a possible extension to 36 months of age. First monthly asymptomatic stool samples collected at 1-12, 15, 18, 21, and 24 months of age were included in analyses of gut function.

LABEL: Stool type, physiologic
DEFINITION: Type of stool type collected, using information from surveillance. 'Diarrhea stools' were samples with a liquid or watery consistency where diarrhea was reported within +/- 2 days of stool collection. 'Monthly stools' were collected more than 2 days away from an episode of study-defined diarrhea. Surveillance was conducted twice weekly for up to 3 years of age to assess illness on all days since the last surveillance visit. Whenever a participant produced at least 3 loose stools in a single day, diarrheal stool samples were collected before the end of the episode. Work up for detection of enteric pathogens was performed on diarrheal stool samples collected until 24 months of age (with a possible extension to 36 months of age) and on first monthly asymptomatic stool samples collected at 1-12, 15, 18, 21, and 24 months of age (with the option to test additional monthly stool samples to 36 months of age).

LABEL: Stool type, severe diarrhea
DEFINITION: Type of stool type collected, using information from surveillance. 'Diarrhea stools' were samples that had a 'Diarrhea severity score' of at least 5 reported within +/- 2 days of stool collection. 'Monthly stools' were collected more than 2 days away from an episode of study-defined diarrhea. Surveillance was conducted twice weekly for up to 3 years of age to assess illness on all days since the last surveillance visit. Whenever a participant produced at least 3 loose stools in a single day, diarrheal stool samples were collected before the end of the episode. Work up for detection of enteric pathogens was performed on diarrheal stool samples collected until 24 months of age (with a possible extension to 36 months of age) and on first monthly asymptomatic stool samples collected at 1-12, 15, 18, 21, and 24 months of age (with the option to test additional monthly stool samples to 36 months of age).

LABEL: Stool used for environmental enteropathy analysis
DEFINITION: Indicator to select the gut function analysis set of stool samples used in PMID: 28396264. Whenever a participant produced at least 3 loose stools in a single day, diarrheal stool samples were collected before the end of the episode. First monthly asymptomatic stool samples were collected every month from 0-24 months of age, with a possible extension to 36 months of age. First monthly asymptomatic stool samples collected at 1-12, 15, 18, 21, and 24 months of age were included in analyses of gut function.

LABEL: Stool weight
DEFINITION: Amount of the stool sample collected (originally reported in grams). First monthly asymptomatic stool samples were collected every month from 0-24 months of age, with a possible extension to 36 months of age. Whenever a participant produced at least 3 loose stools in a single day, diarrheal stool samples were collected before the end of the episode. Diarrheal stool samples were collected until 36 months of age.

First monthly asymptomatic stool samples collected at 1-12, 15, 18, 21, and 24 months of age underwent microbiological testing and gut function testing.
